properly relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Based on the constitutional separation of powers, the judiciary has inherent
2 authority to manage and control its employees, including their selection,
3 appointment, promotion, discipline and termination, and if the other branches of
4 government take any legislative or executive actions that directly interfere with the
5 judiciary’s personnel decisions, such interference violates the separation of powers
6 doctrine because it unconstitutionally infringes on the judiciary’s inherent authority
7 to manage and control its employees. (City of Sparks v. Sparks Mun. Court, 129
8 Nev. 348, 362-66 (2013))
9 Under existing law, in each county whose population is 700,000 or more
10 (currently Clark County), the judge of each district court and the justice of the
11 peace of each justice court may appoint a deputy marshal for the court instead of a
12 bailiff, and the deputy marshal serves at the pleasure of the judicial officer making
13 the appointment. (NRS 3.310, 4.353; State ex rel. Vogel v. Grierson, No. 62225,
14 2014 WL 1226461 (Nev. Mar. 21, 2014) (explaining that deputy marshals “are
15 more like employees than public officers because each ‘deputy marshal serves at
16 the pleasure of the judge he or she serves.’ ”)) As a general rule, when a person
17 serves at the pleasure of the appointing authority, the person is considered to be an
18 at-will employee, and the appointing authority has the right to discharge the person
19 for any reason, with or without cause, so long as the reason does not violate public
20 policy. (Nigro v. Nev. State Bd. of Cosmetology, 103 Nev. 496, 497-98 (1987);
21 Wayment v. Holmes, 112 Nev. 232, 235-36 (1996); Dillard Dep’t Stores, Inc. v.
22 Beckwith, 115 Nev. 372, 376 (1999))
23 This bill revises existing law relating to deputy marshals in each county whose
24 population is 700,000 or more (currently Clark County). First, this bill provides that
