25 the judge of each district court and the justice of the peace of each justice court
26 shall appoint for the court a deputy marshal instead of a bailiff. However, this bill
27 also provides that before such a judicial officer appoints a deputy marshal, the
28 judicial officer must first consider whether there are any qualified and available
29 county employees to serve in the position. Further, this bill provides that after the
30 judicial officer appoints a deputy marshal, regardless of whether the person is a
31 county employee when appointed, the deputy marshal shall be deemed to be a
32 county employee, except that during his or her judicial service: (1) the deputy
33 marshal serves at the pleasure of the judicial officer making the appointment; and
34 (2) the rules and policies that apply to other county employees do not apply to the
35 deputy marshal, unless otherwise provided by the judicial officer.
36 Finally, this bill provides that if the judicial officer ends the service of the
37 deputy marshal in the court of that judicial officer for any reason that does not
38 violate any applicable federal or state law or public policy governing such service,
39 the deputy marshal has no right to serve in that court. However, the deputy marshal
40 remains a county employee and his or her continued employment is subject to the
41 rules and policies that apply to other county employees, including, without
42 limitation, the rules and policies that govern reassignment, transfer, discharge,
43 demotion or discipline.
